1️⃣ Introduction to Databases for SREs

Databases store and organize application data.

A Senior SRE must understand databases to:

Monitor performance and reliability.

Troubleshoot incidents (slow queries, deadlocks, crashes).

Automate backup, restore, and migration processes.

Support high availability, failover, and scaling.

Common DB types:

SQL (Relational): PostgreSQL, MySQL/MariaDB.

NoSQL (Non-relational): Redis, MongoDB, Cassandra.

2️⃣ Installation & Setup
PostgreSQL (Recommended for SQL)
# Ubuntu / Debian
sudo apt update
sudo apt install postgresql postgresql-contrib -y

# CentOS / RHEL
sudo yum install postgresql-server postgresql-contrib -y

# Initialize DB
sudo postgresql-setup initdb   # RHEL/CentOS
sudo systemctl start postgresql
sudo systemctl enable postgresql

# Switch to postgres user
sudo -i -u postgres
psql
MySQL / MariaDB
# Ubuntu / Debian
sudo apt install mysql-server -y

# CentOS / RHEL
sudo yum install mariadb-server -y

sudo systemctl start mariadb
sudo systemctl enable mariadb
sudo mysql_secure_installation
Redis (NoSQL / Cache)
# Ubuntu / Debian
sudo apt install redis-server -y

# CentOS / RHEL
sudo yum install redis -y

sudo systemctl start redis
sudo systemctl enable redis
redis-cli ping   # Should respond PONG
3️⃣ SQL Basics
Connect to DB
# PostgreSQL
psql -U postgres -d mydb

# MySQL
mysql -u root -p
CRUD Operations
-- Create table
CREATE TABLE users (
  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(50),
  email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE
);

-- Insert data
INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES ('Jeffry', 'jeffry@example.com');

-- Read data
SELECT * FROM users;

-- Update data
UPDATE users SET email='new@example.com' WHERE name='Jeffry';

-- Delete data
DELETE FROM users WHERE id=1;
Indexes & Performance
-- Create index to speed up queries
CREATE INDEX idx_users_email ON users(email);

-- View query execution plan
EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM users WHERE email='new@example.com';
4️⃣ Database Administration & Users
PostgreSQL
-- Create user
CREATE USER devops WITH PASSWORD 'securepass';

-- Grant privileges
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE mydb TO devops;

-- Show users
\du
MySQL
-- Create user
CREATE USER 'devops'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'securepass';

-- Grant privileges
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON mydb.* TO 'devops'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

-- Show users
SELECT User, Host FROM mysql.user;
5️⃣ Backup & Restore
PostgreSQL
# Backup DB
pg_dump mydb > mydb_backup.sql

# Restore DB
psql mydb < mydb_backup.sql

# Backup entire cluster
pg_dumpall > full_backup.sql
MySQL / MariaDB
# Backup DB
mysqldump -u root -p mydb > mydb_backup.sql

# Restore DB
mysql -u root -p mydb < mydb_backup.sql
6️⃣ Monitoring & Metrics (SRE Focus)

Key metrics to monitor:

Query throughput (QPS)

Latency of queries

Active connections

Lock and deadlock count

Disk usage

Memory / Cache usage

Replication lag

PostgreSQL
-- Active connections
SELECT * FROM pg_stat_activity;

-- Long running queries
SELECT pid, age(clock_timestamp(), query_start), query
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE state != 'idle';

-- Locks
SELECT * FROM pg_locks;
MySQL
-- Show processlist
SHOW PROCESSLIST;

-- Check slow queries
SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'slow_query_log';
SHOW VARIABLES LIKE 'slow_query_log_file';
Redis
# Check server info
redis-cli INFO

# Monitor commands in real-time
redis-cli MONITOR
7️⃣ High Availability & Replication
PostgreSQL Streaming Replication

One master, one or more replicas

-- On master: edit postgresql.conf
wal_level = replica
max_wal_senders = 3

Set up replica: use pg_basebackup to copy data, configure recovery.conf.

Monitor replication lag:

SELECT * FROM pg_stat_replication;
MySQL Replication

Configure master-slave

-- On master
SHOW MASTER STATUS;

-- On slave
CHANGE MASTER TO MASTER_HOST='master_host', MASTER_USER='replicator', MASTER_PASSWORD='pass', MASTER_LOG_FILE='mysql-bin.000001', MASTER_LOG_POS=123;
START SLAVE;
SHOW SLAVE STATUS\G
Redis Sentinel / Cluster

Sentinel monitors Redis masters and promotes replicas if master fails.

# Example
redis-sentinel sentinel.conf
8️⃣ Troubleshooting & Recovery

Common SRE issues:

Slow queries → use EXPLAIN, optimize indexes

Deadlocks → detect, kill blocking queries

Disk full → remove old logs/backups

Replication lag → check network, redo logs

PostgreSQL
-- Kill long query
SELECT pg_terminate_backend(pid) FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE pid=1234;

-- Check disk usage
\! du -sh /var/lib/postgresql/data/*
MySQL
-- Kill process
KILL 1234;

-- Show database size
SELECT table_schema "DB Name", SUM(data_length + index_length)/1024/1024 "Size (MB)" FROM information_schema.tables GROUP BY table_schema;
9️⃣ Advanced SRE Topics
Performance Tuning

Adjust memory (shared_buffers, work_mem, innodb_buffer_pool_size)

Adjust connection limits

Monitor slow queries and optimize

High Availability & Failover

PostgreSQL: streaming replication + Patroni

MySQL: Group Replication / Galera Cluster

Redis: Sentinel + Cluster

Automation & CI/CD

Scripts for backup, restore, and maintenance

DB migrations via Flyway or Liquibase

Health checks for monitoring pipelines

Advanced Commands
# PostgreSQL: View recent queries
SELECT * FROM pg_stat_statements ORDER BY total_time DESC LIMIT 10;

# Git-like recovery
psql -f db_recovery.sql

# Check replication lag
SELECT now() - replay_timestamp AS lag FROM pg_stat_replication;
